<DOC><DOCNO> AP880303-0247 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 2111EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Dominican-Unrest     03-03 0301</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Dominican-Unrest,0313</SECOND><HEAD>Student Killed, Another Injured on Third Day of Protests</HEAD><BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Protesters demandinglower prices set fire to stores in a third day of disturbancesThursday. A merchant killed one protester and wounded another,authorities said.   Police said 300 people were arrested in Santiago, the Caribbeannation's second-largest city, where soldiers fired tear gas todisperse rioters. Demonstrations were also reported in slumsections of Santo Domingo, the capital.   A Roman Catholic Church leader, Monsignor Agripino NunezCollado, called on leaders of government, labor, business and thechurch to begin talks on the demonstrations and the country'seconomic problems.   Protests against inflation broke out last week in eight of the26 Dominican provinces, leaving five people dead and 20 injured. OnSaturday, President Joaquin Balaguer announced a 25 percentincrease in the monthly minimum wage to about $75, but newdemonstrations broke out this week.   On Thursday, protesters set fire to an undetermined number ofstores in Santiago and hurled firebombs at businesses in SantoDomingo.   A merchant in the city fired a gun into a mob that tried to burndown his store, killing Miguel Cruz Vazquez, 21, and woundingAndres Antonio Batista, 18, police said.   Protest organizers, grouped as the Front for Popular Resistanceand Popular Unity Council, said demonstrations would continueFriday and Saturday if the government did not move to curbinflation.   The government has made no comment on the latest violence. Lastweek, Balaguer threatened to call out the army to contain unrest.   Inflation was 30 percent last year, according to privateeconomists, and might top 50 percent this year.   The protests have been the worst since Balaguer took office 1{years ago in the nation of more than 6.5 million people.</TEXT></DOC>